    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i already checked the MAF and it seems okay. i'm mostly worried about vacuum leaks or maybe something with the fuel delivery. how do i narrow down if it's actually a vacuum leak vs a fuel injector issue?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you're suspecting a vacuum leak, one way to narrow it down is to use a smoke test. This involves introducing smoke into the vacuum system and watching for it to escape, which would indicate a leak. However, given your specific case, here's a more targeted approach. \n\nTo check for vacuum leaks, do the following:\n\n1. Inspect all vacuum lines, including connections and gaskets. Look for wear, cracks, or disconnected hoses.\n2. Pay special attention to the hose that feeds the MAF sensor and where it goes into the intake manifold; these are common leak points.\n\nAs for fuel delivery issues, to verify proper fuel injector performance, you'd need a specialized fuel injector cleaning kit or consider having them professionally tested at a repair shop. Remember, diagnosing these issues involves checking each potential problem in turn while ruling out others. If you continue to experience problems, consult a professional mechanic, as deeper engine diagnostics may be required.",
      "source": "target",
